WEBVTT

00:07.000 --> 00:09.400
NARRATOR: On this episode
of Life Below Zero,

00:09.433 --> 00:13.033
as winter nears its end,
new obstacles arise.

00:13.067 --> 00:16.400
SUE: In the end, I'm not the
one with control out here,
Mother Nature is.

00:16.433 --> 00:19.133
NARRATOR: The Hailstones' hunt
takes a turn for the worse.

00:19.167 --> 00:22.433
AGNES: There's a fox
over there, I'm gonna
take a shot. Fuck!

00:22.467 --> 00:25.800
NARRATOR: Andy stalks
a lethal predator
to protect his livelihood.

00:25.833 --> 00:28.433
I got multiple wolf tracks
in this slough here.

00:28.467 --> 00:31.533
NARRATOR: Erik and
Martha's plans
come to a screeching halt.

00:31.567 --> 00:32.633
It's not gonna happen.

00:32.667 --> 00:34.433
NARRATOR: And Sue
races to clear a path.

00:34.467 --> 00:37.600
SUE: A plane must have
a runway to safely land.

00:57.600 --> 00:58.633
There we go.

00:58.667 --> 01:00.200
We're gonna cut up
this moose quarter.

01:00.233 --> 01:03.033
It's the last one that we have
from the moose we harvested
this past fall.

01:03.067 --> 01:05.967
It's a ham, really tasty,
prime cut piece.

01:06.000 --> 01:08.233
I'll hack the bone
out of here.

01:08.267 --> 01:11.233
Start taking apart
the muscle groups.

01:11.267 --> 01:13.100
When we kill a moose
or kill a caribou,

01:13.133 --> 01:15.833
the bones are full
of marrow and they're
really great for soup,

01:15.867 --> 01:18.133
and then, you know,
animals like moose or caribou,

01:18.167 --> 01:20.833
where the hide
isn't worth anything,
we use that for trapping bait.

01:20.867 --> 01:23.467
And there's really
something to do with most
parts of any animal.

01:25.800 --> 01:30.333
NARRATOR: Erik
and Martha Salitan
rely on the animals they hunt

01:30.367 --> 01:33.433
to maintain a subsistence
lifestyle in the Arctic.

01:35.000 --> 01:38.167
You wanna scrap together
a smoker and smoke
some of this meat?

01:38.200 --> 01:40.433
Yeah, that could
be fun, different.

01:40.467 --> 01:43.867
-Break up the cuisine
a little bit?
-Mmm-hmm.

01:45.967 --> 01:48.133
Harvesting your own meat,
it's very fulfilling.

01:48.167 --> 01:51.900
You feel a lot better knowing
that you butchered the animal,

01:51.933 --> 01:53.367
it's all good quality meat,

01:53.400 --> 01:57.133
and makes you feel
a little bit more independent
living in the bush.

01:57.167 --> 02:01.000
Well, I'm done. Let's go out
and check out what we got
for building materials.

02:01.033 --> 02:03.400
Sounds good. I'm done, too.

02:03.433 --> 02:06.167
I'll go put this outside
where it'll be cold.

02:06.200 --> 02:08.733
MARTHA: So Erik and I
just got done
butchering the moose.

02:08.767 --> 02:11.400
We're gonna go out
to the hangar and hopefully
find the materials

02:11.433 --> 02:14.600
that we need to put together
a, uh, usable smoker.

02:19.833 --> 02:23.533
ERIK: The type of smoker
that we're looking to make
is a cold smoker.

02:23.567 --> 02:25.133
It just adds a little bit
more flavour.

02:25.167 --> 02:27.067
It doesn't add
any nutritional value.

02:27.100 --> 02:28.700
It has nothing to do
with life or death,

02:28.733 --> 02:31.033
it's just a little
spice of life.

02:31.067 --> 02:34.433
Doing these small kind
of projects is fun 'cause
it's like a change of pace,

02:34.467 --> 02:37.133
something different
than the daily chores.

02:37.167 --> 02:39.367
It's nice to be able
to build something yourself

02:39.400 --> 02:41.867
and to be able to also take
the meat that you've harvested

02:41.900 --> 02:45.567
and throw it in there
and make an edible,
finished product.

02:45.600 --> 02:47.233
ERIK: I'm gonna use
these 2 x 6s

02:47.267 --> 02:50.400
that are left over
from building this hangar
this past summer.

02:50.433 --> 02:54.133
We're gonna go six feet deep,
six feet wide, and put
a six-foot roof on there.

02:54.167 --> 02:56.067
MARTHA: Now we just got
one more wall to go,

02:56.100 --> 02:58.200
which is the wall that's gonna
have the door in it.

02:58.233 --> 03:00.400
Then we're gonna
throw on the sheeting.

03:00.433 --> 03:02.467
We got a lot of work
ahead of us.

03:04.433 --> 03:06.233
ANDY: We give up a lot
to live out here

03:06.267 --> 03:09.200
because we want a certain type
of quality of life.

03:09.233 --> 03:11.567
And a big part
of that quality of life

03:11.600 --> 03:14.567
is utilising the resources
that are here for us.

03:26.433 --> 03:28.933
I'm preparing right now
to start making

03:28.967 --> 03:33.067
a bunch of snares
for predator trapping.

03:33.100 --> 03:37.767
And, um, we don't have
a lot of moose
per square mile here.

03:37.800 --> 03:41.500
Part of that problem
is because of predators,
uh, namely, wolves.

03:41.533 --> 03:45.367
Any kind of predator control
is very emotional
for a lot of people.

03:45.400 --> 03:47.267
Most people are either
for it or against it.

03:47.300 --> 03:50.067
There's very few people
that are middle ground.

03:50.100 --> 03:52.467
Um, I tend to be kind of
middle ground on it, though,

03:52.500 --> 03:54.233
because I realise,

03:54.267 --> 03:57.333
as much as I don't
like killing animals,

03:57.367 --> 04:01.200
um, it's absolutely necessary
if I want to be able
to eat in the future.

04:02.567 --> 04:04.667
I'm getting older,
and so I want to make sure

04:04.700 --> 04:07.233
that there's a good
moose population in my area

04:07.267 --> 04:10.233
so that I don't have
to work so hard
to feed myself every year.

04:14.033 --> 04:17.533
For me, going a year without
a moose is really bad.

04:19.567 --> 04:23.167
That's probably the equivalent
of someone's house
burning down,

04:23.200 --> 04:25.567
losing their job,
and their car explodes.

04:25.600 --> 04:28.267
Your world is gone
if you don't have
moose or caribou

04:28.300 --> 04:29.633
in the freezer for the winter.

04:30.767 --> 04:32.567
I've now made my loop.

04:32.600 --> 04:34.333
I like to make
my loops pretty big.

04:34.367 --> 04:37.433
Uh, the wolves,
they don't like going
through something small,

04:37.467 --> 04:40.033
so I tend to make
my loops fairly big.

04:40.067 --> 04:41.733
Uh, and when
the animal goes in,

04:41.767 --> 04:45.867
this slides very easily
in one direction, here.

04:45.900 --> 04:47.900
And then,
once it tightens down,

04:47.933 --> 04:51.067
it's very difficult
to get it to unlock.

04:51.100 --> 04:53.000
It's pretty simple method
to make these.

04:53.033 --> 04:55.333
Not too terribly expensive

04:55.367 --> 04:58.833
and, um,
can be very efficient.

05:02.667 --> 05:06.000
Wolves are probably
the single hardest thing
to trap or snare up here.

05:06.033 --> 05:07.500
They're incredibly smart.

05:07.533 --> 05:09.000
They have an incredible
sense of smell,

05:09.033 --> 05:12.833
so they can smell steel
underneath the snow
or hanging in the woods.

05:12.867 --> 05:15.000
This year,
when I killed my moose,
I saved the hide,

05:15.033 --> 05:20.433
I saved the head,
but I also saved all the guts
and I put them in a tote.

05:20.467 --> 05:23.867
They've been sitting in a tote
all fall and into the winter.

05:23.900 --> 05:26.900
Ooh, yeah.

05:26.933 --> 05:28.167
Smells ripe.

05:28.200 --> 05:30.267
These wolves
are going after moose,

05:30.300 --> 05:33.467
so I think the moose guts
is probably gonna
be my best bet.

05:35.133 --> 05:37.367
And that'll be my main bait.

05:37.400 --> 05:40.700
Got some moose guts for bait.

05:40.733 --> 05:43.200
I got holes in them
so I can tie them
up to a tree.

05:43.233 --> 05:47.367
The one thing I don't have
is I don't have
much daylight left.

05:47.400 --> 05:50.633
It's pretty much gone
off the mountain here now,

05:50.667 --> 05:52.333
which means I got
about an hour or so.

05:52.367 --> 05:54.867
That's not enough time to get
out and make these sets.

05:57.100 --> 05:59.200
It's a one-shot deal
when you do this

05:59.233 --> 06:01.300
and we'll get an early start
tomorrow morning.

06:04.033 --> 06:06.567
SUE: I did not choose
to leave society.

06:06.600 --> 06:09.267
I am just living my own life.

06:09.300 --> 06:13.333
Only with the freedom
of isolation
does my little light shine.

06:21.567 --> 06:24.400
I've got a snow machine coming
out to help me with my chores.

06:24.433 --> 06:26.700
(COUGHS) Snow machine won't
fit into a regular plane.

06:26.733 --> 06:28.567
It's gotta be a bigger plane.

06:28.600 --> 06:31.733
And, uh, there's a Caravan,

06:31.767 --> 06:34.800
a little bit larger plane
than I usually get
during the winter.

06:34.833 --> 06:39.100
But the key to getting
the Caravan in was getting
the runway ready for it.

06:39.133 --> 06:43.433
NARRATOR: Sue Aikens
relies on planes to deliver
supplies into Kavik.

06:43.467 --> 06:45.367
Maintaining her
mile-and-a-half runway

06:45.400 --> 06:49.267
is crucial for her survival
and can take days to complete.

06:50.600 --> 06:53.200
SUE: If a big plane tries
to land, you know,

06:53.233 --> 06:57.400
going 200 miles an hour
and tries to land on ice,
on sheet ice, glare ice,

06:57.433 --> 07:00.800
all's they're gonna do is be
a new storage unit
off the end of my runway.

07:00.833 --> 07:04.100
Gonna go work on the runway,
try to get as much snow
off of it as I can.

07:04.133 --> 07:07.500
I'm hoping if I can get
the initial layer of snow
off down to the ice,

07:07.533 --> 07:09.933
the sun will do the rest
of the work for me.

07:09.967 --> 07:12.233
If I can't do that,
I can't get the Caravan in.

07:12.267 --> 07:14.167
Can't get the Caravan in,

07:14.200 --> 07:16.400
well, then somebody
in Deadhorse gets
my snow machine

07:16.433 --> 07:18.567
as a lawn decoration.
(CHUCKLES)

07:24.500 --> 07:28.367
I don't take the clearing
or the maintaining
of the runway lightly at all.

07:28.400 --> 07:31.900
Most of these bush pilots
and pilots that come out here
are people that I know.

07:31.933 --> 07:34.233
They're cool people.

07:34.267 --> 07:37.800
A plane must have
a decent runway

07:37.833 --> 07:40.700
that they can count on
to safely land.

07:40.733 --> 07:44.233
Doesn't matter how badly
I want to get
whatever's on that plane.

07:44.267 --> 07:47.967
I will never risk
somebody's life to get it.

07:48.000 --> 07:49.733
I take that very seriously.

07:52.167 --> 07:53.900
I'm gonna go ahead
and drag this section.

07:53.933 --> 07:57.033
Gonna attach my drag,
that's this thing
under the snow.

07:57.067 --> 08:00.467
And it's gonna cut and move
the top layer of snow.

08:00.500 --> 08:02.000
Right now it may seem light,

08:02.033 --> 08:03.900
but this is after
10:00 at night,

08:03.933 --> 08:06.100
so my temperatures are gonna
go down a little bit.

08:06.133 --> 08:07.733
Um, before
everything refreezes,

08:07.767 --> 08:10.733
I wanna knock that clear
and let the sun
work on it tomorrow.

08:19.867 --> 08:21.467
I heard the engine knocking.

08:21.500 --> 08:24.267
If I keep pushing it
and it breaks down
on the runway,

08:24.300 --> 08:27.133
then I've shut down
my entire runway
to even skied landings.

08:30.467 --> 08:33.767
I had to take a drag off this,
she's done.

08:33.800 --> 08:37.633
I have to get her in the shop,
let it warm up,
take a look at it tomorrow.

08:39.433 --> 08:41.533
If I can't get this thing
going tomorrow,

08:41.567 --> 08:45.033
I don't get a snow machine
in a Caravan,
that's the way that is.

08:47.067 --> 08:50.467
AGNES: In this harsh country,
there's nobody just gonna
appear and help you.

08:50.500 --> 08:53.733
You have to be comfortable
and have an idea
of what you're doing

08:53.767 --> 08:57.167
before you just decide
to just get up
and go out into the country.

09:11.067 --> 09:12.867
Is it cold out, Chip?

09:12.900 --> 09:14.567
CHIP: It's getting
a little breezy,

09:14.600 --> 09:16.367
so I would dress warm
if I were you.

09:16.400 --> 09:18.933
NARRATOR: Chip and Agnes
have set up camp in Kiwalik,

09:18.967 --> 09:21.467
110 miles from their home
in Noorvik,

09:21.500 --> 09:25.200
to capitalise on the region's
vast resources
of caribou and fur.

09:25.233 --> 09:27.167
CHIP: We've had terrible winds
and terrible weather

09:27.200 --> 09:29.500
and in the time that we've had
to wait for the weather,

09:29.533 --> 09:31.600
the caribou have gotten
closer and closer.

09:31.633 --> 09:32.733
Now the caribou are here.

09:32.767 --> 09:35.533
-Whoa, bright.
-Yeah, it is bright.

09:35.567 --> 09:38.367
There should be a small herd
of caribou roaming around,

09:38.400 --> 09:40.833
so we're just gonna
go check out the flats
and the lower hills

09:40.867 --> 09:42.533
and, uh, see
what we've come across.

09:42.567 --> 09:46.367
After three, four days,
we pretty much consumed
all our extra food we brought,

09:46.400 --> 09:48.567
so we just need camp meat.

09:48.600 --> 09:51.767
I'll bet you the caribou
are closer
than they were yesterday.

09:51.800 --> 09:54.833
CHIP: One thing that's nice
is the caribou are moving
closer to camp every day.

09:54.867 --> 09:59.067
Caribou are herd animals.
They all wanna be together.
They wanna be in large groups.

09:59.100 --> 10:00.967
So they're forming up right
now and they're forming up,

10:01.000 --> 10:02.233
and they're following
each other,

10:02.267 --> 10:04.533
and they're gonna be
passing through here.

10:04.567 --> 10:05.833
Our good days are here.

10:09.533 --> 10:11.467
CHIP: Yeah, no, let's head up
to the, to the, um, trail

10:11.500 --> 10:12.600
-and take the hard trail.
-The trail.

10:12.633 --> 10:15.233
And we'll save gas that way.

10:15.267 --> 10:18.500
The best thing we can do here,
because we wanna hunt
in a short distance

10:18.533 --> 10:20.033
and because we wanna
have an easier hunt

10:20.067 --> 10:22.000
is to let the animals
come to us.

10:22.033 --> 10:25.500
So when we got the animals
coming closer and closer,
it saves us gas,

10:25.533 --> 10:28.700
it saves us parts,
it saves us time,
it saves us a lot of energy.

10:32.233 --> 10:35.900
AGNES: Pretty much gonna stay
down low where it's not
too windy, not too cold.

10:35.933 --> 10:39.633
We just go ride round through
the back and watch the herd

10:39.667 --> 10:42.800
and see if there's any fur
or anything else around.

10:45.700 --> 10:48.833
There's a fox over there!
I'm gonna get closer
and take a shot!

10:57.233 --> 10:58.300
Fuck!

11:03.200 --> 11:05.233
There goes my ride.

11:06.000 --> 11:08.600
I let go of my handlebar.

11:08.633 --> 11:14.867
I sit up, and I grab my rifle,
and it got stuck
in my handlebar.

11:16.133 --> 11:18.267
And then it turned me.

11:19.333 --> 11:20.667
Fuck!

11:21.533 --> 11:25.033
Oh, God, over
a stupid fucking fox.

11:27.000 --> 11:28.867
CHIP: Wow,
I didn't see you crash.

11:28.900 --> 11:31.067
If I saw her standing there,
and I saw the fox running,

11:31.100 --> 11:33.167
and I didn't see her aiming
or trying to shoot at it.

11:33.800 --> 11:35.633
-Are you okay?
-No.

11:37.467 --> 11:40.333
Well, the rifle went right
through the fucking, uh...

11:41.733 --> 11:43.300
Right through the tank.

11:43.333 --> 11:46.233
(EXHALES) Well, you know,
here on the tundra,
it's bumpy.

11:46.267 --> 11:49.200
And if you go too fast
and you hit too big of a bump,
you can get thrown off,

11:49.233 --> 11:53.633
you get your machine
flipped over, you can get,
um, you can just crash.

11:53.667 --> 11:56.933
As long as you're okay,
I can fix this.

11:56.967 --> 11:58.233
Okay?

11:58.267 --> 12:00.467
AGNES: Fucking,
stupid fucking fox.

12:00.500 --> 12:02.567
CHIP: You could sit here
and cry, and hoo
and ha over this shit.

12:02.600 --> 12:04.667
It doesn't fix plastic
or metal.

12:04.700 --> 12:09.067
We need to get it back to camp
so we can put it on a cargo
sled and take it home.

12:09.100 --> 12:13.000
Or we need to, um, leave
it the fuck here and just
carry on with ourselves.

12:13.033 --> 12:15.033
We need to go get
you another rifle.

12:17.900 --> 12:20.133
AGNES: Oh, God, it's...

12:20.167 --> 12:22.067
Fuck!

12:22.100 --> 12:23.833
Bent.

12:23.867 --> 12:25.333
Broken.

12:25.367 --> 12:29.500
Not only did I break
my best rifle,

12:29.533 --> 12:32.300
I totally broke my gas tank.

12:32.333 --> 12:34.367
Handlebars won't even turn.

12:34.400 --> 12:37.933
My windshield is all smashed
up into many pieces.

12:37.967 --> 12:39.867
CHIP: There's a lot
of structural damage
to this thing.

12:39.900 --> 12:42.000
-It's not a pretty sight.
-Sorry about that.

12:42.033 --> 12:44.500
It's not you,
I'm glad you're okay.

12:44.533 --> 12:46.067
Don't be sorry to me.

12:46.100 --> 12:48.933
I've crashed snow machines,
I know just exactly
how you're feeling.

12:48.967 --> 12:51.833
We still got one ride,
there's no reason to go back
unless my ride's totalled,

12:51.867 --> 12:54.300
and then we've got yours
for parts and we'll still
make it home.

12:54.333 --> 12:56.300
-Okay. Well, that's
a good way...
-So buck up.

12:56.333 --> 12:58.500
-...to look at it.
-It'll be all good, yeah.
We're gonna be good.

12:58.533 --> 13:00.067
-Get ready?
-Yeah, put your stuff on it

13:00.100 --> 13:01.967
and let's just tow this thing
back to camp now.

13:02.000 --> 13:04.100
Having two machines
has always been our premise.

13:04.133 --> 13:06.967
When one machine's down,
we can continue on
while we fix the other one.

13:07.000 --> 13:08.633
I think you gotta just
quit worrying about it.

13:08.667 --> 13:12.167
We've always, always,
always figured it out.

13:20.800 --> 13:24.833
MARTHA: As far as waste goes,
I guess that comes full circle
with everything that we have.

13:24.867 --> 13:28.300
Whatever we can use,
we'll utilise it,
so, nothing goes to waste.

13:44.000 --> 13:46.267
ERIK: Working on my skid here,
drilling a hole in.

13:46.300 --> 13:47.933
I'm gonna attach a rope
between the two of them

13:47.967 --> 13:51.100
and then I'm gonna be able
to pull the smokehouse
around with a truck,

13:51.133 --> 13:53.700
a four-wheeler,
a snow machine,
a tractor, whatever.

13:53.733 --> 13:55.000
NARRATOR: In Wiseman,

13:55.033 --> 13:58.000
Erik and Martha are using
resources that surround them

13:58.033 --> 14:00.533
as well as salvage materials
from past builds

14:00.567 --> 14:03.100
for the construction
of a new smokehouse.

14:04.533 --> 14:06.400
MARTHA: We're putting up
the sheet metal here,

14:06.433 --> 14:10.833
which is not only going
to complete the smokehouse,
but make it sturdier.

14:10.867 --> 14:12.933
Feed it up on the top there.

14:12.967 --> 14:15.033
MARTHA: So far progress
has been real fast.

14:15.067 --> 14:17.267
We have four walls,
we've got the roofs all ready.

14:17.300 --> 14:19.933
We've pounded it out
and we're just gonna
keep moving.

14:19.967 --> 14:23.200
Is it gonna fit?

14:23.233 --> 14:26.300
We're gonna get this door
on hinges, make sure it flows
the way we want it.

14:26.333 --> 14:28.433
Then we'll sheet
the son of a gun.

14:28.467 --> 14:30.233
MARTHA: Between our
fishing lodge in Iliamna

14:30.267 --> 14:32.000
and our hunting lodge up here
in the Brooks Range,

14:32.033 --> 14:33.400
we've always got
a lot going on.

14:33.433 --> 14:36.500
So it's nice to be able
to work on our own
little projects

14:36.533 --> 14:38.967
at our own pace
and do what we wanna do.

14:43.000 --> 14:44.333
ERIK: It's gotta come up
a touch more.

14:44.367 --> 14:46.367
Yup, right there.

14:49.600 --> 14:50.633
(DRILLING)

14:55.467 --> 14:57.700
Nice.

14:57.733 --> 14:59.700
-And it's solid.
-Yeah.

14:59.733 --> 15:03.433
And the first moose we smoke
in there is the moose
that antlers it is.

15:03.467 --> 15:07.500
I'm just pumped to drag it
out of here and, uh, fire
it up for the first time.

15:10.700 --> 15:13.133
ANDY: Everything changes
in the wintertime up here.

15:13.167 --> 15:14.433
Everything gets harder.

15:14.467 --> 15:16.033
You have to be
twice as careful.

15:16.067 --> 15:17.733
You don't take chances.

15:17.767 --> 15:20.967
If you do have a problem,
you don't have
a lot of time to react.

15:27.500 --> 15:29.267
(BARKING)

