whether I can reschedule
it for tomorrow.

32:22.533 --> 32:27.200
It cost me 500 bucks just to,
in the fuel to work the runway
the last day and a half.

32:27.233 --> 32:28.767
But it's just part of the risk
of being here.

32:28.800 --> 32:32.267
I can plan for it,
and I can get ready for it,
and in the end,

32:32.300 --> 32:34.767
I'm not the one with control
out here, Mother Nature is.

32:35.800 --> 32:38.767
Last night, I was trying
to clear the runway

32:38.800 --> 32:41.667
and the Bobcat started having
some power issues.

32:41.700 --> 32:45.200
I have a feeling my hydraulic,
uh, pump is going out.

32:46.133 --> 32:48.667
I'm gonna top it off

32:48.700 --> 32:50.433
with a little bit
of hydraulics.

32:51.833 --> 32:53.067
It's not feeling happy.

32:53.100 --> 32:55.367
So, I either get it done

32:55.400 --> 32:58.800
or bust it down trying.

32:58.833 --> 33:01.133
I mean, everything else
has been failing this year,

33:01.167 --> 33:03.033
might as well go for broke
and get it all.

33:04.867 --> 33:08.967
I've decided I'm gonna
go ahead and push this thing
as hard as I can today.

33:09.000 --> 33:11.733
It may be a mistake,
I may end up
with a lawn decoration.

33:11.767 --> 33:13.533
Even if the Caravan
can't come in,

33:13.567 --> 33:15.300
there's other pilots
flying around.

33:15.333 --> 33:17.800
They're gonna think it's safe,
and it's not.

33:17.833 --> 33:20.133
So I've gotta go see
if I can't just finish
dragging it

33:20.167 --> 33:21.700
and then let nature
do its business.

33:21.733 --> 33:24.033
At least then,
I've given it my all.

33:26.133 --> 33:28.133
I'm definitely risking
the equipment.

33:28.167 --> 33:30.267
I know I have to replace
the hydraulic pump.

33:30.300 --> 33:32.300
I know I've got
filters to replace.

33:32.333 --> 33:34.667
I know I've got some issues.

33:34.700 --> 33:36.900
I'm hoping that
it just holds its own.

33:36.933 --> 33:40.333
These birds need to be
safely on the ground.

33:40.367 --> 33:43.867
They need to know Kavik
is a place to go and be safe.

33:46.833 --> 33:49.500
The runway is as good
as I can get it.

33:49.533 --> 33:55.000
I am pleased that I got
a good mile, solid mile
of the runway

33:55.033 --> 33:57.033
done nice and smooth.

33:58.200 --> 33:59.967
Do one more check in the
morning,

34:00.000 --> 34:02.100
verify that it's still
in good shape,

34:02.133 --> 34:04.733
and, uh, when he calls,
I'll give him
the honest report.

34:04.767 --> 34:06.000
Away we go.

34:08.733 --> 34:10.967
ERIK: Day in and day out,
I wanna be out in the woods,

34:11.000 --> 34:12.433
I want to be hunting,
I want to be trapping,

34:12.467 --> 34:15.533
I want to be flying,
I want to be fishing.

34:15.567 --> 34:17.933
That's why I run off
and come live
out in the woods.

34:33.733 --> 34:37.233
MARTHA: So, uh, our meat's
been smoking in here
for a couple hours.

34:38.700 --> 34:41.100
Should been long enough
to give it a good, smoky taste

34:41.133 --> 34:42.900
from that alder
we put in there.

34:42.933 --> 34:46.267
I'm gonna go and grab
a good piece
for dinner for Erik and I.

34:50.800 --> 34:53.467
Looking good in here.

34:53.500 --> 34:57.967
I think I'm gonna go with
this one right here.
Right on the top shelf.

34:58.000 --> 34:59.467
Took this one
off the top shelf,

34:59.500 --> 35:03.100
so I guess it's what you would
call a top-shelf meat.

35:03.133 --> 35:04.567
Nice.

35:04.600 --> 35:05.967
Gonna go cook it up.

35:10.200 --> 35:15.333
Um, smoker was a good little
project for Erik and I.

35:15.367 --> 35:18.633
That was a little bit
of a challenge there at the
end when it came apart,

35:18.667 --> 35:21.867
but, uh, Erik and I
always, uh,

35:21.900 --> 35:25.467
overcome whatever issues
we have out here,
which you gotta do anyway.

35:25.500 --> 35:29.600
You can't rely on anybody
else but yourselves,
so you work independently.

35:29.633 --> 35:31.633
It's really cool to think
that just not too long ago,

35:31.667 --> 35:36.233
Erik and I were brainstorming
up this idea about this whole
smokehouse, and, uh,

35:36.267 --> 35:39.367
built the smoker and then
smelled the fruits of our
labour.

35:42.033 --> 35:44.533
-Do you like it?
-Mmm-hmm.

35:44.567 --> 35:46.667
I'd say that smoker
worked out pretty good.

35:46.700 --> 35:48.100
Mmm-hmm.

35:50.200 --> 35:51.400
Real good.

35:57.233 --> 35:59.767
ANDY: I really don't need
a lot to live
out in this country.

35:59.800 --> 36:02.300
I have the skills,
and I know how
to get the resources,

36:02.333 --> 36:04.567
and I know how
to utilise the resources.

36:04.600 --> 36:09.100
I think living the way I live
is one of the easiest ways
in the world to live.

36:18.500 --> 36:19.733
Burning daylight.

36:23.700 --> 36:26.033
It's time to go
check snares and traps.

36:26.067 --> 36:29.533
These traps and snares
have been out
for a little over a week.

36:29.567 --> 36:31.800
I got skunked at my first set.

36:32.267 --> 36:33.300
There you go.

36:33.333 --> 36:35.300
Second time's a charm
is what I'm hoping for.

36:36.233 --> 36:39.267
Let's go, yeah! All right!

36:39.300 --> 36:42.833
There's no one thing
that a person makes
his living on out here.

36:42.867 --> 36:45.233
You have to be multi-talented.

36:45.267 --> 36:49.167
You have to be
kind of an opportunist.

36:49.200 --> 36:53.100
I don't think I'll ever
stop trapping, even when
I'm 70 years old.

36:53.133 --> 36:55.333
Attaboys. On by. Let's go.

36:55.367 --> 36:56.933
Straight ahead. Let's go.

37:00.367 --> 37:03.867
Well, looks like, uh,
I'm at the end
of my line here.

37:05.267 --> 37:09.767
Go check some snares
and a few marten sets.

37:09.800 --> 37:12.933
And I'm not seeing any
disturbances in the trees.

37:12.967 --> 37:14.967
So there's a snare there.

37:17.533 --> 37:19.667
There's my bait set over here.

37:21.733 --> 37:23.733
One here.

37:23.767 --> 37:26.833
A little bit early on,
anything big coming
through here,

37:26.867 --> 37:29.267
but I'm gonna leave all these
snares where they're at.

37:29.300 --> 37:32.800
The longer they're out here,
the better chance I have
of catching something.

37:35.500 --> 37:39.300
I think I'll, I'll head on
back and go check
the rest of my traps.

37:39.333 --> 37:42.567
And there's two more
marten sets and we'll go back

37:42.600 --> 37:45.067
and see if I have a little
bit of luck in that area.

37:47.567 --> 37:50.700
It kind of looks like there's
something hanging there.

37:56.000 --> 37:57.467
Yeah, baby!

37:57.500 --> 37:59.367
So we've got one marten here.

38:01.500 --> 38:03.000
All right!

38:03.033 --> 38:06.867
He's frozen solid,
so he was definitely caught
in the cold weather.

38:06.900 --> 38:08.933
It's been a few days.

38:08.967 --> 38:11.367
I feel good there's one,
let's go check
some more traps,

38:11.400 --> 38:12.833
see if I have any more luck.

38:14.933 --> 38:16.200
Yeah, buddy!

38:17.500 --> 38:19.133
Hello, Mr Marten.

38:20.500 --> 38:22.600
All right.

38:22.633 --> 38:24.400
That's a nice-looking marten.

38:25.333 --> 38:28.900
So that's two.
That makes me feel good.

38:28.933 --> 38:31.467
I like coming home
with something in this bag.

38:33.033 --> 38:34.733
We're good to go.

38:34.767 --> 38:38.333
It's a pretty productive area.
We'll just keep setting,
hopefully we'll keep catching.

38:39.167 --> 38:40.567
Good day today.

38:40.600 --> 38:42.333
Look at that, Tope.

38:42.367 --> 38:47.567
Didn't pick up any wolves,
but I've got two nice marten,
and, uh, so I've got some fur.

38:49.333 --> 38:52.100
Didn't do any real predator
control to help
the moose right now,

38:52.133 --> 38:54.833
but it's just
a matter of time.

38:54.867 --> 38:56.367
Time and patience.

38:58.400 --> 39:00.633
Okay, let's go home. Yeah!

39:00.667 --> 39:02.000
Go home and skin some marten.

39:04.933 --> 39:08.167
Marten skins peel off
pretty easily
once you get going.

39:09.767 --> 39:10.933
And once it gets
to this point,

39:10.967 --> 39:13.100
I usually like
to hang them up.

39:21.067 --> 39:24.767
Go slow and easy right here
'cause I don't wanna tear it.

39:24.800 --> 39:27.767
Trapping is probably
the only way that a person
out in the bush

39:27.800 --> 39:30.100
can be guaranteed
making some money.

39:30.133 --> 39:32.300
Um, you know,
I say all the time,

39:32.333 --> 39:35.733
the only way to really live
out here is you gotta
diversify what you're doing.

39:35.767 --> 39:37.800
Fact remains that I have
to make a living, too

39:37.833 --> 39:43.500
and this is one
of the few ways that I can
supplement my income.

39:43.533 --> 39:45.000
There we go.

39:47.700 --> 39:50.900
And so now what I need
to do is I need to put it
on the board

39:50.933 --> 39:52.467
with the flesh side out.

39:52.500 --> 39:55.667
I'm gonna stretch it out
and that's gonna dry
in that shape,

39:55.700 --> 40:00.833
and that gives it a certain
form that the fur buyers like.

40:00.867 --> 40:04.400
Generally speaking,
I'd say 90 bucks
for one animal like this.

40:04.433 --> 40:05.800
I've got one of them
skinned out.

40:05.833 --> 40:07.800
This one's still
a little bit stiff.

40:07.833 --> 40:10.067
He's not quite
ready to skin out,

40:10.100 --> 40:13.600
so we'll let this guy
sit here and thaw out
a little bit more.

40:17.467 --> 40:21.833
So this was a pretty,
pretty good day for me.
I picked up a couple marten.

40:21.867 --> 40:26.000
I didn't pick up any wolves,
but, uh, for the amount
of time that I put into it,

40:26.033 --> 40:31.267
it's good to get a little bit
of fur here and, um, keep
adding to my collection.

40:31.300 --> 40:36.400
And as time goes on,
I'm hoping that I'll pick up
a wolf or two in those snares.

40:36.433 --> 40:39.500
I'll just keep at it
all winter long,
see what I end up with.

40:41.167 --> 40:42.633
It was a good day.

40:46.433 --> 40:48.167
SUE: Mother Nature and I
are always kind of

40:48.200 --> 40:50.067
playing a game of cards,
it's like poker.

40:50.100 --> 40:52.300
Occasionally, she deals
herself a winning hand.

40:52.333 --> 40:54.733
You know, and I just gotta
wait till we shuffle again.

40:54.767 --> 40:57.600
You know, eventually
I'll get my, uh, full house.

41:04.467 --> 41:06.267
Good bit of news, finally.

41:06.300 --> 41:11.400
It's been several days
with this storm and the fog
is now finally pulling back.

41:11.433 --> 41:13.867
Supposed to be blue bird
in the next couple of hours.

41:13.900 --> 41:17.100
So I'm just checking
the runway with the wind
that we've had.

41:17.133 --> 41:18.700
What kind of drifts
have built up?

41:18.733 --> 41:21.933
What do I need to do
to make this
a perfect landing?

41:21.967 --> 41:27.267
So I'm going up and down
and seeing, how wide can I
tell them is a good area?

41:27.300 --> 41:30.000
How long of an area
is acceptable?

41:30.033 --> 41:31.667
It's looking pretty good!

41:31.700 --> 41:34.567
The eastern end of the runway
looks beautiful.

41:34.600 --> 41:37.033
If he sticks to the centre,
he's got a good run.

41:37.067 --> 41:40.667
But I'm gonna mark
some of these drifts
with my machine.

41:40.700 --> 41:45.700
I mark the drifts by just
running over the drift
with the Argo.

41:45.733 --> 41:48.267
And that's gonna leave a trail

41:48.300 --> 41:54.100
and he'll be able to see
from the air,
stay between the lines.

41:54.133 --> 41:58.600
Because it's not bad,
it's just I care a lot about
the safety of these guys.

42:05.133 --> 42:07.167
It's just beautiful,
blue skies.

42:07.200 --> 42:10.167
Uh, no obscurations at all.

42:10.200 --> 42:13.400
I'm really happy,
yay, a new toy.

42:13.433 --> 42:16.767
But actually, I...
Serious face, it's a new tool.
(SNORTS)

42:24.167 --> 42:27.667
These guys live 500 miles
away from me,
but any time I need them,

42:27.700 --> 42:28.867
bam, they're there.

42:31.133 --> 42:32.800
-How are you doing, Sue?
-Good. How are you doing?

42:32.833 --> 42:33.967
-Pretty good.
-Thank you.

42:34.000 --> 42:35.267
-Good to see you.
-Yeah, you, too.

42:35.300 --> 42:36.833
I appreciate all the help.

42:36.867 --> 42:38.200
How was the runway?

42:38.233 --> 42:39.467
-The runway's good, yeah.
-Okay.

42:39.500 --> 42:42.433
Dirk got here safely
and the snow machine is here.

42:42.467 --> 42:45.300
The Argo was a
go-slow-and-get-
there-and-back.

42:45.333 --> 42:46.833
This is a go-fast.

42:46.867 --> 42:50.867
Time for me to see
what I can do here.

42:52.633 --> 42:54.167
(ENGINE STARTS)

42:54.200 --> 42:55.633
Yay!

42:57.967 --> 43:02.567
It seemed like Mother Nature
dealt herself a winning hand
on the old weather conditions.

43:02.600 --> 43:04.400
Susie pulled out
a royal flush in the end.

43:04.433 --> 43:09.633
It's a beautiful day,
he landed no problems,
and I've got my new "tool."

43:10.400 --> 43:11.733
Yay!

43:14.100 --> 43:15.267
Got a new tool.
